"Castro J., Zamora R., Hódar J.A., Gómez J.M.","Alleviation of summer drought boosts establishment success of Pinus sylvestris in a Mediterranean mountain: An experimental approach",2005,"Plant Ecology","181","2",,"191","202",,,10.1007/s11258-005-6626-5,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-28244457845&partnerID=40&md5=932b4fe7714edf99a5651cdfb2675d13","Grupo de Ecología Terrestre, Departamento de Biología Animal Y Ecología, Universidad de Granada, E-18071 Granada, Spain","Castro, J., Grupo de Ecología Terrestre, Departamento de Biología Animal Y Ecología, Universidad de Granada, E-18071 Granada, Spain; Zamora, R., Grupo de Ecología Terrestre, Departamento de Biología Animal Y Ecología, Universidad de Granada, E-18071 Granada, Spain; Hódar, J.A., Grupo de Ecología Terrestre, Departamento de Biología Animal Y Ecología, Universidad de Granada, E-18071 Granada, Spain; Gómez, J.M., Grupo de Ecología Terrestre, Departamento de Biología Animal Y Ecología, Universidad de Granada, E-18071 Granada, Spain","We performed an irrigation experiment to study the impact of summer drought on Pinus sylvestris establishment at its southernmost distribution limit. Watering was done during the first growing season simulating mesic summer conditions, and we monitored the consequences for survival and growth during the first growing season and the delayed consequences on the second growing season. In addition, we considered the heterogeneity created by the microhabitats, where seeds are found after dispersal (bare soil, under shrubs, and under adult pines). Summer drought was the main mortality factor in all the microhabitats. Watering increased emergence and doubled seedling survival compared to non-watered control sites. Differences were even higher when the cumulative effect on emergence and survival was considered, with an overall recruitment of 22.4% in watered plots vs. 7.9% in control. Irrigation increased growth in bare soil and under shrubs, but had scant effect on growth under pines, suggesting that radiation was the limiting factor in this microhabitat. The positive effect of irrigation on growth parameters persisted during the second growing season despite water was not added the second year, showing delayed consequences of drought on seedling performance. Summer drought thus limits Pinus sylvestris establishment in these southernmost forests by reducing both recruitment and growth. This might lead to the development of a remnant dynamic in these relict populations under the current regional increase in dryness and rainfall variability associated with global warming. © Springer 2005.","Growth-survival conflicts; Irrigation experiments; Mediterranean ecosystems; Pinus sylvestris","drought; experimental study; growth; seedling establishment; survival; Pinus sylvestris",,,,,,"Bennett, K.D., (1997) Evolution and Ecology: The Pace of Life, , Cambridge University Press Cambridge; Boratynski, A., Giertych, M., Mátyás, C., Range of natural distribution (1991) Genetics of Pinus Sylvestris, pp. 19-30. , Akadémiai Kiadó Budapest; Broadmeadow, M.J., Jackson, S.B., Growth response of Quercus petraea Fraxinus excelsior Pinus sylvestris to elevated carbon dioxideozone and water supply (2000) New Phytol., 146, pp. 437-451; Broncano, M.J., Riba, M., Retana, J., Seed germination and seedling performance of two Mediterranean tree species, holm oak (Quercus ilex L.) and Aleppo pine (Pinus halepensis Mill.): A multifactor experimental approach (1998) Plant Ecol., 138, pp. 17-26; Canadell, J., Zedler, P.H., Arroyo, M.T.K., Zedler, P.H., Fox, M.D., Underground structures of woody plants in Mediterrranean ecosystems of AustraliaCaliforniaand Chile (1995) Ecology and Biogeography of Mediterranean Ecosystems in ChileCaliforniaand Australia, pp. 177-210. , Springer-Verlag Berlin; Canham, C.D., Berkowitz, A.R., Kelly, V.R., Lovett, G.M., Ollinger, S.V., Schnurr, J., Biomass allocation and multiple resource limitation in tree seedlings (1996) Can. J. F